    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Encoder-Only Means"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A transformer encoder-only model takes a sequence of tokens and produces a contextualized vector for each token position. It has "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "no decoder"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — it cannot generate text by predicting the next token. What it can do very well is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "understand"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " text: classify it, extract information from it, or embed it into a semantic vector space."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The key property is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "bidirectional attention"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": every token attends to every other token, both left and right, in a single forward pass. This gives each output vector full sentence context — the representation of \"bank\" in \"banking rules\" incorporates the word \"rules\" just as much as the word \"banking\"."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Left: attention pattern comparison — encoder sees all tokens (full green grid), decoder-only sees only past tokens (lower triangle). Center: MLM pre-training masking 'cat' and predicting it from context. Right: BERT-base architecture with 12 stacked encoder blocks, task heads (classification, NER, QA), and variant comparison table."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BERT Architecture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers, Devlin et al., 2018) is the canonical encoder-only model. BERT-base stacks 12 identical encoder blocks. Each block has two sub-layers, each wrapped in a residual connection and LayerNorm:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Multi-Head Self-Attention"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": 12 attention heads, each computing scaled dot-product attention over all token pairs. Output dimension: 768."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Feed-Forward Network (FFN)"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": two linear layers with GELU activation. Inner dimension: 3072; output dimension: 768."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Input to the first block is the sum of three learned embedding tables: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "token"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (vocabulary lookup), "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "segment"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (A or B, for sentence-pair inputs), and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "position"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (learned, up to 512 positions)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pre-training Objectives"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Masked Language Modeling (MLM)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "15% of input tokens are randomly selected. Of those:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "80% are replaced with "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "[MASK]"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "10% are replaced with a random token"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "10% are left unchanged"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The model predicts the original token at each masked position using the surrounding context from both directions. The 10%/10% split is needed because the model never sees "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "[MASK]"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tokens at inference time; the noise prevents it from simply learning to copy unmasked tokens."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Next Sentence Prediction (NSP)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BERT is also trained to predict whether sentence B follows sentence A (50% real pairs, 50% random). The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "[CLS]"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " token's final vector is used for this binary prediction. Later work (RoBERTa) found NSP adds little value and removed it — the MLM objective alone produces strong representations."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Fine-Tuning for Downstream Tasks"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The pretrained BERT checkpoint is loaded and a small task-specific head is added on top. The whole network is then fine-tuned end-to-end on labeled data for a few epochs."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"bert-base-uncased\")\nmodel = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(\n    \"bert-base-uncased\",\n    num_labels=2,  # e.g. positive / negative\n)\n\nbatch = tokenizer(\n    [\"The movie was great!\", \"Terrible experience.\"],\n    padding=True,\n    truncation=True,\n    return_tensors=\"pt\",\n)\n\noutputs = model(**batch)\nlogits = outputs.logits          # shape: (2, 2)\npredictions = logits.argmax(-1)  # tensor([1, 0])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The library provides task-specific wrappers for the common patterns:"
          }
        ]
      },
